 assimilation policies. Niezen shows how, from a new position of legitimacy and influence, they are striving for greater recognition of collective rights, in particular their rights to self-determination in international law. These efforts are influencing local politics in turn and encouraging more ambitious goals of autonomy in indigenous communities worldwide.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aEthnicityxPolitical aspects. 0aHuman rights. 0aIndigenous peoplesxCivil rights. 0aIndigenous peoplesxEthnic identity. 0aIndigenous peoplesxPolitics and government. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  a20th century.  acollective rights.  acultural issues.  aeconomic development.  aglobalism.  ahistorical perspective.  ahistory of indigenism.  ahuman rights.  aidentity.  aindigenism.  aindigenous communities.  aindigenous peoples.  ainternational indigenism.  ainternational labor organization.  ainternational movements.  ainternational organizations.  anonfiction.  anongovernmental organizations.  apolitical activists.  apolitical issues.  apolitical perspective.  asense of self.  asocial activism.  asocial reform.  auniversal rights.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093669040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520936690423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520936690/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles